******************SWITCH CASE*******************

A switch statement without any case is not possible.
Duplicate case labels are not allowed within the same switch block; they must be unique values.
The switch statement in Java supports the following data types:
Primitive types: byte, short, char, int.
Wrapper classes: Byte, Short, Character, Integer.
Enumerated types (enum).
String: String was introduced as a supported type for switch in Java 7.

example:


import java.util.Scanner;
public class Main {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		Scanner sc= new Scanner(System.in);
		System.out.println("enter the Fisrt latter of day");
		char a=sc.next().charAt(0);
		switch (a) {
		case 's':
			System.out.println("its sunday");
			break;
		case 'm':
			System.out.println("monday");
			break;
		case 'w':
			System.out.println("its Wednesday");
			break;
		case 't':
			System.out.println("its Thursday");
			break;
		case 'S':
			System.out.println("its Saturday");
			break;
		default:
			System.out.println("enter valid");
			break;
		}
	}
}


